Today is the birthday of Enrico Fermi
\f1\b0  (1901-1954), Italian and naturalized-American physicist and the creator of the world's first {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_reactor"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 nuclear reactor}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Pile-1"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Chicago Pile-1}}. He has been called the "architect of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_Age"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 nuclear age}}" and the "architect of the atomic bomb". He was one of very few physicists to excel in both {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoretical_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theoretical physics}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 experimental physics}}. \
Fermi held several patents related to the use of nuclear power, and was awarded the 1938 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nobel Prize in Physics}} for his work on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Induced_radioactivity"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 induced radioactivity}} by neutron bombardment and for the discovery of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transuranium_elements"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 transuranium elements}}. He made significant contributions to the development of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 statistical mechanics}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 quantum theory}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 nuclear}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particle_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 particle physics}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 Fermi's first major contribution involved the field of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 statistical mechanics}}. After {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfgang_Pauli"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Wolfgang Pauli}} formulated his {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pauli_exclusion_principle"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 exclusion principle}} in 1925, Fermi followed with a paper in which he applied the principle to an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_gas"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 ideal gas}}, employing a statistical formulation now known as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermi%E2%80%93Dirac_statistics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Fermi\'96Dirac statistics}}. Today, particles that obey the exclusion principle are called "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermion"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fermions}}". Pauli later postulated the existence of an uncharged invisible particle emitted along with an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electron}} during {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_decay"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 beta decay}}, to satisfy the law of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conservation_of_energy"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 conservation of energy}}. Fermi took up this idea, developing a model that incorporated the postulated particle, which he named the "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutrino"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 neutrino}}". His theory, later referred to as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermi%27s_interaction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Fermi's interaction}} and now called {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weak_interaction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 weak interaction}}, described one of the four {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_interaction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fundamental interactions}} in nature. Through experiments inducing radioactivity with the recently discovered {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutron"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 neutron}}, Fermi discovered that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_neutron"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 slow neutrons}} were more easily {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutron_capture"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 captured}} by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_nucleus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 atomic nuclei}} than fast ones, and he developed the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermi_age_equation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Fermi age equation}} to describe this. After bombarding {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorium"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 thorium}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uranium"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 uranium}} with slow neutrons, he concluded that he had created new elements. Although he was awarded the Nobel Prize for this discovery, the new elements were later revealed to be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_fission_product"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 nuclear fission products}}.\
\

\f0\b \'c8 oggi il compleanno del grandissimo Enrico Fermi, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisico"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b0 \cf4 fisico}}
\f1\b0 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inventore"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 inventore}} e {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accademico"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 accademico}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italia"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 italiano}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naturalizzazione"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 naturalizzato}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati_Uniti_d%27America"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 statunitense}}. Noto principalmente per gli studi {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisica_teorica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 teorici}} e {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisica_sperimentale"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 sperimentali}} nell'ambito della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meccanica_quantistica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 meccanica quantistica}}, e in particolare della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisica_nucleare"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fisica nucleare}}, tra i maggiori contributi si possono citare la teoria del {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decadimento_beta"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 decadimento \uc0\u946 }}, la {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistica_di_Fermi-Dirac"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 statistica quantistica di Fermi-Dirac}} e i risultati riguardanti le {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forza_nucleare_forte"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 interazioni nucleari}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 Progett\'f2 e guid\'f2 la costruzione del primo {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reattore_nucleare_a_fissione"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 reattore nucleare a fissione}}, che produsse la prima {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reazione_nucleare"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 reazione nucleare}} a catena controllata e fu in seguito uno dei direttori tecnici del {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progetto_Manhattan"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Progetto Manhattan}}, che port\'f2 alla realizzazione della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bomba_atomica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 bomba atomica}} nei {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 laboratori di Los Alamos}}. \'c8 stato inoltre tra i primi ad interessarsi alle potenzialit\'e0 della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulazione_numerica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 simulazione numerica}} in ambito scientifico, nonch\'e9 l'iniziatore di una seconda scuola di fisici sia in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italia"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Italia}}\cf4  (i famosi ragazzi di via Panisperna)\cf2 , sia negli {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati_Uniti_d%27America"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Stati Uniti d'America}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 Ricevette nel 1938 il {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premio_Nobel_per_la_fisica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Premio Nobel per la fisica}}, per "
\f2\i l'identificazione di nuovi elementi della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioattivit%C3%A0"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 radioattivit\'e0}} e la scoperta delle {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reazione_nucleare"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 reazioni nucleari}} mediante {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neutrone"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 neutroni}} lenti
\f1\i0 ". In suo onore venne dato il nome ad un elemento della {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tavola_periodica_degli_elementi"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 tavola periodica}}, il {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermio"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fermio}} (simbolo Fm), ad un sottomultiplo del metro comunemente usato in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisica_atomica"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fisica atomica}} e nucleare, il {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Femtometro"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fermi}}, nonch\'e9 a una delle due classi di particelle della statistica quantistica, i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermione"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fermioni}}.\
